This file consists of data analyses done for the manuscript: “Serial passage of the human probiotic E. coli Nissle in an insect host leads to changed bacterial phenotypes”

Persistence analysis

library(ggplot2)
#loads raw data into dataframe
persistence_data <- read.table("Persistence_EcN.csv", sep = ";", header=TRUE)

#shows data
persistence_data

#saves treatment strain names to list
namelist <- c("L1", "L2", "L3", "L4","L5","L6","L7","L8","L9","L10","A")

#creates empty dataframe with treatment strains as columns
pers_rate_df <- data.frame("L1"=rep(NA,7), "L2"=rep(NA,7),"L3"=rep(NA,7),"L4"=rep(NA,7),"L5"=rep(NA,7),"L6"=rep(NA,7),"L7"=rep(NA,7),"L8"=rep(NA,7),"L9"=rep(NA,7),"L10"=rep(NA,7),"A"=rep(NA,7))

#sets days as rows
row.names(pers_rate_df) <- c("day1", "day2", "day3", "day4", "day5", "day6", "day7")

# sets for loop counter to 0
x <- 0

#calculates and saves persistence rates based on the raw data for each treatment and day
for (name in namelist){
  #print(name)
  
  x <- x + 1
  y <- 1
  
  for (day in 1:7){
    pers_rate <- (sum(persistence_data[,2]==name & persistence_data[,3]==day & persistence_data[,4]==1) / sum(persistence_data[,2]==name & persistence_data[,3]==day))
    #print(pers_rate)
    pers_rate_df[y,x] <- pers_rate
    y <- y + 1
  }}
print(pers_rate_df)


#reorganizes the rows and columns of the persistence rates data frame to fit the required input format of ggplot2
pers_gg_input <- data.frame("sample"=1:77, 
                            "persrate"=c(pers_rate_df$L1, pers_rate_df$L2, pers_rate_df$L3, pers_rate_df$L4, pers_rate_df$L5, pers_rate_df$L6, pers_rate_df$L7, pers_rate_df$L8,pers_rate_df$L9,pers_rate_df$L10, pers_rate_df$A), 
                            "day"=rep(1:7,11), 
                            "replicate"=c(rep("L1",7), rep("L2",7), rep("L3",7),rep("L4",7), rep("L5",7), rep("L6",7), rep("L7",7), rep("L8",7), rep("L9",7), rep("L10",7), rep("A",7)))


#plots the persitence rates
ggplot(pers_gg_input, aes(y = persrate, x = day, colour = replicate))+ 
  geom_line(size=1, alpha= 0.8)+
  theme_bw()+
  #ylim(0,1)+
  #theme(legend.position = "none")+
  xlab("Days since exposure")+ 
  ylab("Persistence rate")+ 
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=10),axis.title=element_text(size=10,face="plain"))+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1,2,3,4,5,6,7))+ 
  scale_y_continuous(limits=c(0,1), breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = 10))+
  #ggtitle("EcN persistence")+
  theme(text=element_text(size=10))+
  scale_colour_manual("Replicate", breaks = c("A", "L1","L2"
                                              ,"L3","L4","L5","L6"
                                              ,"L7","L8","L9","L10"),values = c("#8b0000","#2a5ea9"
                                                                                ,"#7096eb", "#1711a0" 
                                                                                ,"#5e5ab8" ,"#3d05ed"
                                                                                ,"#0000ab","#6c23c9"
                                                                                ,"#09aced","#105495"
                                                                                ,"#7048eb"))+
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "lightgrey"), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"))

Using glmer to analyze the differences in persistence between the treatment lines. Data is binomial: Presence or absence of colonies

library(lme4)
gm1 <- glm(cbind(Growth, Day) ~ Treatment,data = persistence_data, family = binomial)

Testing assumptions

#tests assumptions, doesn't test residual distribution, because of the binomial structure (1-colony presence ,0-no presence)
#cooks distance-for model without random effects:
max(cooks.distance(gm1))# should be <1.#
[1] 0.004348977
max(abs(dffits(gm1)))# differences of <1 are fine. 
[1] 0.1538038

Since the model fits, we will create a null model and run anova

g0 <-glm(cbind(Growth, Day)~1,data=persistence_data,family=binomial)  
anova(gm1,g0,test="Chisq")
Analysis of Deviance Table

Model 1: cbind(Growth, Day) ~ Treatment
Model 2: cbind(Growth, Day) ~ 1
  Resid. Df Resid. Dev  Df Deviance Pr(>Chi)
1      1511     1190.9                      
2      1521     1202.4 -10  -11.495   0.3203

There is no difference in persistence between the treatment lines

Growth analysis

Raw data from the Tecan plate reader was adjusted and sorted for the analysis - File is melted_mead_d_sorted


mean_d_melt_sorted <- read.table("melted_mean_d_sorted.csv", sep = ";", header=TRUE) 

#shows data
mean_d_melt_sorted

#adding a treatment column based on the stain name for grouping in plots and analyses

mean_d_melt_sorted$treatment <- NA                ## Adds a column called treatment

for (i in rownames(mean_d_melt_sorted)) {         ## This for loop checks to which treatment each sample belongs and adds the according name to the new "treatment" column
  
  ifelse(rownames(mean_d_melt_sorted)[as.numeric(i)] %in%  grep("blank", mean_d_melt_sorted$strain), mean_d_melt_sorted$treatment[as.numeric(i)] <- "blank",
         ifelse(rownames(mean_d_melt_sorted)[as.numeric(i)] %in%  grep("F", mean_d_melt_sorted$strain), mean_d_melt_sorted$treatment[as.numeric(i)] <- "F",
                ifelse(rownames(mean_d_melt_sorted)[as.numeric(i)] %in%  grep("L", mean_d_melt_sorted$strain), mean_d_melt_sorted$treatment[as.numeric(i)] <- "L", mean_d_melt_sorted$treatment[as.numeric(i)] <- "A")))
  
  
}



#plot
library(ggplot2)
library(cowplot)
#Excludes blanks. Blanks were used as a negative control
means_no_blanks <- droplevels(subset(mean_d_melt_sorted,strain != "blank"))

Plotting the curves

c<-ggplot(means_no_blanks, aes(x=time, y=OD, group=strain)) +
  #geom_point(size=0.5, col="grey") + 
  geom_line(size = 0.8, aes(x=time, y=OD, color= treatment), alpha=0.8)+
  theme(text=element_text(size=10))+
  ggtitle("")+
  theme(strip.background = element_blank())+
  labs(y=  "Absorbance (\u03bb = 600 nm)", x="Time (hours)", tag = "")+
  scale_color_manual("Treatment",labels = c("Ancestral", "Flour passaged", "Larvae passaged"),values=c("#8b0000", "#eead0e", "#00008b"))+
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(), axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"))

c+  scale_x_log10()

Analyzing the growth For statistics we use the output file of the plate reader (but sorted, with all columns named as required). We will now run the growthcurver function on every biological replicate (strain), excluding blanks.



mean_d <- read.csv("mean_d.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")

#The ID column "X" needs to be removed otherwise growthcurver would analyze this as sample ODs
mean_d$X <- NULL


#install.packages("devtools")
#devtools::install_github("sprouffske/growthcurver")
library("growthcurver")


#mean_analysis is the variable with all the measurements. We use it to perform normal stats as we would with any dependent variable




mean_analysis <- SummarizeGrowthByPlate(mean_d, bg_correct = "blank") ## analyzes mean growth curves 

write.csv(mean_analysis,"mean_analysis.csv")                          ## saves analysis as csv file


#show mean_analysis
mean_analysis


# Diagnostics

library(dplyr)
library(magrittr)

# Plots a histogram of the sigma values in order to check for outliers. High sigma values are not good
hist(mean_analysis$sigma, main = "Histogram of sigma values", xlab = "sigma")

# Show the top 5 samples with the largest sigma value 
# (with the worst model fit to the growth curve data)
mean_analysis %>% top_n(5, sigma) %>% arrange(desc(sigma))

# Checks if growthcurver returned any notes (errors) for any growth curve
# from SummarizeGrowthByPlate
mean_analysis %>% filter(note != "") 

#Stats
# loads the data
mean_analysis_sorted <- read.csv("mean_analysis_sorted.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")

From the values we got, we will analyze growth rate (r) and carrying capacity (k) First normality test of growth rate and carrying capacity

library("lme4")
library("lmerTest")
library("car")
library("influence.ME")

#Normality test

shapiro.test(mean_analysis_sorted$r)  # r is not normally distributed

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  mean_analysis_sorted$r
W = 0.88755, p-value = 0.03504
shapiro.test(mean_analysis_sorted$k)  #k is not normally distributed

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  mean_analysis_sorted$k
W = 0.84691, p-value = 0.007573
#p-value < 0.05 implying that the distribution of the data is significantly different from normal distribution

Growth rate analysis

Analysis was done with Kruskal test followed with pairwise Wilcox test, Benjamini-Hochberg adjusted p-values.

kruskal.test(r ~ treatment, data = mean_analysis_sorted)

    Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test

data:  r by treatment
Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 10.889, df = 2, p-value = 0.00432
pairwise.wilcox.test(mean_analysis_sorted$r, mean_analysis_sorted$treatment,
                     p.adjust.method = "BH")

    Pairwise comparisons using Wilcoxon rank sum exact test 

data:  mean_analysis_sorted$r and mean_analysis_sorted$treatment 

  A      F     
F 0.0065 -     
L 0.0065 0.6991

P value adjustment method: BH

Survival analysis

We first analyzed T. castaneum larvae that were fed with EcN and then put on PBS - to see if there is any effect of E.coli pretreatment on the survival.

library (survival)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggfortify)
library(survminer)
library(coxme)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(car)
library(lme4)
data1<- read.table("Survival.txt", header =TRUE, sep="\t" )
##only PBS plates
dataP<-subset(data1,Treatment=="P")

#shows data
dataP


plotP<-survfit(Surv(dataP$Day.of.Death, dataP$Survival)~dataP$Pretreatment)
plot(plotP)


surv_CP<-ggsurvplot(plotP,data=dataP, fun=NULL, legend = "bottom",main=NULL,xlab="Time(days)",palette="Dark2", legend.title= "Treatment",legend.labs = c("Ancestral","K12","L2","L5","L6","PBS"))
surv_CP +ggtitle("Survival upon exposure to ECN")

We will use coxph because we only have one random effect(Plate). By using coxph we can check for assumptions of the model.

res <- coxph(Surv(Day.of.Death, Survival)~Pretreatment+frailty(Plate), data=dataP, method="efron")


#(1) Schoenfeld residuals

cox.zph(res)
             chisq  df    p
Pretreatment  2.95 5.0 0.71
GLOBAL        2.95 9.4 0.97
#proportional hazards are met

#(2) Influential observations (akin to dfbetas in linear regression)

dfbeta=residuals(res, type="dfbeta")
max(abs(dfbeta))
[1] 0.06646418
hist(dfbeta)


#The value is <2 so it is ok to proceed

Null model and anova

res0 <-coxph(Surv(Day.of.Death,Survival)~1 + frailty(Plate),data=dataP)

anova(res,res0,test="Chisq")
Analysis of Deviance Table

qPCR analyis

Att1 analysis

Checking for distribution

shapiro.test(Att1$dCp) 

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  Att1$dCp
W = 0.95289, p-value = 0.4722

Parametric test one way anova since data are normally distributed

a1 <- aov(Att1$dCp ~ Att1$Sample) 
#checking the assumptions for anova 
plot(a1)

hat values (leverages) are all = 0.1666667
 and there are no factor predictors; no plot no. 5

Levene test to check the variance

leveneTest(dCp ~ Sample, data = Att1)
group coerced to factor.
Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
      Df F value Pr(>F)
group  2  0.1877 0.8308
      15

The assumptions are met so we can perform anova
